english:
  title: Preface to the Collected Works of Master Yuljeong
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Literature dwells in the outer world, yet its roots run deep into the heart. The heart's expression is bound to the times, and so one who recites poetry cannot help but be moved by the rightness and transformations of the classical tradition. In these latter days, the prosaic and fragmented dominate, and we should not be surprised that the true voice has ceased to sound. By rare fortune, a lone phoenix may cry out among the sparrows, yet its song is carried away by the wind, and as it travels farther and farther, the echo becomes forever beyond our reach. Alas, what sorrow!

    Master Yuljeong possessed a magnificent spirit. He mastered the Spring and Autumn Annals and devoted himself to the prose selections of Xiao Tong, from which his own literary brilliance emerged. His teacher, Master Ikjae, would often say, "Your writings carry an ancient nobility." Yet what we have recorded now amounts to so little—why? When the Master grew old by the Kumgang River, calamity struck: a fire consumed his dwelling, and his manuscripts perished with it. Only what his grandson Sojong had heard with his ears and seen with his eyes remained.

    The Master's son-in-law was Court Official Huh Shik, skilled in composition. His son, Cho, rose to become Chief of Military Records and Director of the Imperial Examinations, and now serves as Inspector of Jeolla Province. He wished to publish this collection and asked me to write this preface. When I was young, I studied under the Master; the Court Official instructed me as well; and Sojong became my disciple. By every measure of righteousness, I could not refuse. Thus I write these words. As for the Master's greater deeds and circumstances, these are recorded in the official histories, and I shall not repeat them here.
  footnotes:
    - Yuljeong (栗亭) was the pen name of Master Rok, whom the author greatly respected.
    - The reference to a lone phoenix among sparrows is a classical image of rare excellence surrounded by the ordinary.
    - Xiao Tong's Wen Xuan (文選) was the preeminent anthology of Chinese literature and a foundational text for East Asian literati.
    - The Kumgang River (錦江) flows through what is now central Korea, indicating the Master's residence.
    - The various official titles mentioned reflect the hierarchical bureaucratic structure of the Goryeo period.
